---
import BaseLayout from '@/layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import { loadArticles } from '@/lib/articles/load-articles';
import { categories } from '@/lib/categories/categories';

const articles = await loadArticles();
const projects = new Set(articles.flatMap((a) => a.sources.map((s) => s.project)));
const description =
  'Why this knowledge base exists, how it was built from real project decisions, and how to read — or challenge — it.';
---

<BaseLayout title="About" description={description}>
  <article class="prose page">
    <h1>About this knowledge base</h1>
    <p class="lede">
      This is a written record of how I build software — the practices, conventions and
      hard-won lessons that govern my code, architecture, testing, tooling and design
      decisions. It exists to be read, used, and argued with.
    </p>

    <h2>Why it exists</h2>
    <p>Four reasons, in order of how much they matter to me:</p>
    <ol>
      <li>
        <strong>To make the knowledge current.</strong> Practices accumulate across
        projects as scattered notes. Collecting them in one place, dated and sourced,
        turns tacit habit into something I can review and keep honest.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>To check that I build the way I intend.</strong> Writing each practice
        down — with the incident that justifies it — makes it falsifiable. Where an
        article is wrong or out of date, it can be corrected here, and the correction
        flows back into how the work is actually done.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>To sharpen the skill system.</strong> These articles are the raw material
        for a more precise set of reusable skills. See <a href="/skills">Skills</a> for the
        proposed shape.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>To share it with other developers.</strong> Everything here is general
        enough to be useful beyond the project it came from.
      </li>
    </ol>

    <h2>How it was built</h2>
    <p>
      Every article is distilled from a real decision on a real project — not invented for
      this site. The source material was a global conventions file, six coding-standard
      skills, and roughly eighty dated notes captured while working across
      {projects.size} projects. Those were grouped into {categories.length} categories and
      {articles.length} deep-dive articles, each carrying its <em>provenance</em>: which
      project it came from and when.
    </p>

    <h2>Newer decisions override older ones</h2>
    <p>
      A practice is only as good as its last revision. Where two decisions conflict, the
      more recent one wins, and the article says so explicitly with both dates. For
      example, one project removed Effect-TS during a move to a pure SPA on 2026-03-15,
      then re-adopted it nine days later in a Grand Refactoring on 2026-03-24 — so the
      standing practice is <a href="/kb/functional-architecture/errors-as-values-with-effect"
        >errors as values with Effect</a
      >, and the earlier note is recorded as superseded rather than deleted.
    </p>

    <h2>How strongly each practice is held</h2>
    <p>Every article carries a severity badge:</p>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Non-negotiable</strong> — never up for debate; violating it is a defect.</li>
      <li><strong>Strong</strong> — the default; deviate only with an explicit, recorded reason.</li>
      <li><strong>Preferred</strong> — the house style; reasonable exceptions exist.</li>
      <li><strong>Contextual</strong> — situational guidance that depends on the project.</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>How to read it — and challenge it</h2>
    <p>
      Start with the <a href="/">non-negotiables</a> on the home page, then browse by
      topic. If an article contradicts your experience, the provenance is there so you can
      weigh the evidence: a practice backed by a two-day production outage is held more
      firmly than one backed by a single preference. Disagreement that comes with a better
      argument is exactly what keeps this current.
    </p>

    <h2>Built with what it documents</h2>
    <p>
      This site is its own proof. It is an Astro&nbsp;5 static site with Lit islands loaded
      client-side (never SSR-rendered on the edge), strict TypeScript with no
      <code>any</code>/<code>as</code>/<code>null</code>, a functional core of small pure
      functions unit-tested with Vitest, event-driven Playwright E2E with no timeouts, and
      Biome enforcing the rules in CI — every one of which is a practice documented inside it.
    </p>
  </article>

  <style>
    .page {
      padding: var(--space-8) 0;
    }
    .lede {
      font-size: var(--step-1);
      color: var(--text-muted);
    }
    ol,
    ul {
      padding-inline-start: 1.2em;
    }
    li {
      margin: var(--space-2) 0;
    }
  </style>
</BaseLayout>
